I also had the same issue where Hibernate was detecting a dirty context on fields which were using custom converters to save classes as JSON fields, causing Hibernate to perform unnecessary UPDATE operations on every SELECT query.

    @Entity
    @DynamicUpdate
    @Table(name = &quot;MyEntity&quot;)
    public class MyEntity {
        
        @Column(name = &quot;MyClass&quot;)
        @Convert(converter = MyClassConverter.class) // Converts to JSON string
        private MyClass myClassField;
        
        // Other fields
    }

In my case, the problem was that the classes utilizing the custom converters were not implementing the Serializable interface, which would cause Hibernate to detect the deserialized object as changed.

Adding `implements Serializable` to the classes using the custom converter and generating their serialVersionUID fixed the problem. Hibernate no longer detects a dirty context right after retrieval, and no longer does unnecessary UPDATE queries.

    public class MyClass implements Serializable {
    
        private static final long serialVersionUID = 3838227336741360928L;
        // MyClass fields...
    }

Remember to implement Serializable on all classes of any nested class members, as otherwise you will get an error when the field serialization happens.

