This is documented in the JavaDoc for [Object.wait()](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/21/docs/api/java.base/java/lang/Object.html#wait(long,int)) (note added emphasis):

&gt; This method causes the current thread (referred to here as T) to place itself in the wait set for this object and then **to relinquish any and all synchronization claims on this object**.

Note that this is required: how else could the main thread execute

        synchronized (testString) {
            testString.notify();
        }

if the lock on `testString` was still held by any of the threads that you started.

BTW `testString` is a terrible name: it is not a string, it doesn&#39;t have anything to do with tests, it distracts from understanding its purpose.

